# Concept Reuse — Core Concepts Library

## Philosophy

Every technology is a bundle of well-known building blocks assembled for a specific problem and set of tradeoffs. `materials/core-concepts/` is a tool-agnostic reference library that captures these building blocks once. Technology-specific lessons (SQL, NoSQL, Python, Docker, etc.) **must** link back to it whenever a concept appears, reinforcing that:

1. The concept is **not new** — it exists independently of the technology being taught
2. The technology **chose** this concept because of the problem it solves and the tradeoffs it accepts
3. Other technologies make **different choices** from the same toolkit — and the student has already seen (or will see) those alternatives

The goal: students learn to approach any new technology by asking *"which concepts does this implement, and what tradeoffs did it make?"* instead of treating each tool as an isolated thing to memorize.

## Rules for Technology-Specific Lessons

### Always link to core-concepts

When a lesson touches a concept that exists in `core-concepts/`, add a blockquote callout linking to the generic explanation:

```
> **Core Concept:** See [Trees for Storage](../../core-concepts/02-data-structures/02-trees-for-storage.md) for how B-trees work in general. PostgreSQL uses B-trees for indexes because it needs sorted access for range scans.
```

The callout must explain **why this technology chose this concept** — not just link to it.

### Highlight tradeoff differences

When the current technology made a different choice than another technology the students have seen, call it out explicitly:

```
> MongoDB uses B-trees (WiredTiger), while Cassandra uses LSM-trees — same problem (disk-based storage), different tradeoff (read-optimized vs write-optimized).
```

### README concept maps

Each technology module's `README.md` should include a concept map table showing which core-concepts appear and why — see `materials/sql/README.md` and `materials/nosql/README.md` for the established format.

### Don't duplicate — reference

Core-concepts files own the generic explanation. Technology lessons should explain only the technology-specific application and link out for the theory. If a lesson is explaining B-trees from scratch instead of linking to `core-concepts/02-data-structures/02-trees-for-storage.md`, refactor it.

## When Creating New Content

- Check `materials/core-concepts/README.md` for the concept-to-technology matrix
- If the lesson introduces a concept not yet in `core-concepts/`, create the generic file first, then link to it
- Update the matrix in `core-concepts/README.md` when adding a new technology column or concept row
